An Isotopic Perspective into the Magmatic Evolution and Architecture of the Rift Zones of KÄ«lauea Volcano

Abstract

The basic model for the plumbing system of KÄ«lauea Volcano states that (1) compositionally distinct batches of primitive mantle-derived magma ascend through a primary conduit to the volcanoâs summit magma storage reservoir and (2) this olivine-controlled magma is mixed and stored prior to eruption at the summit or lateral intrusion into the East Rift Zone (ERZ) or Southwest Rift Zone (SWRZ) for further storage, mixing, differentiation and/or eruption. In detail, however, the magmatic architecture of KÄ«laueaâs rift zones and their connection to the summit reservoir and the deeper source(s) of melt from the Hawaiian mantle plume, is more complicated. Here we use the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic compositions of historical KÄ«lauea summit and rift lavas, from 1959 to the recent eruptions at PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å and HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u, to test models for the volcanoâs rift zones and decipher their magmatic evolution. These samples (including a 1919 summit lava) record a rapid and systematic variation in 206Pb/204Pb (18Â·39 to 18Â·66), 87Sr/86Sr (0Â·70347 to 0Â·70364), and ÎµNd (+5Â·9 to +6Â·5) that derives from changes in the composition of the parental magma delivered to the volcano. Assimilation of the Pacific oceanic crust and/or the Hawaiian volcanic edifice does not significantly modify the isotopic composition of mantle-derived KÄ«lauea magmas. Many contemporaneous summit and rift lavas display small, but statistically significant, differences in 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr that are used to (1) identify magma batches from the mantle and (2) track their movement though the ERZ and/or SWRZ. A series of intrusions from the summit reservoir to the ERZ in the 1960s left behind a large amount of magma that became a prominent mixing component in subsequent rift lavas. Variations in the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of lavas from the Mauna Ulu rift eruption (1969â1974) are mostly related to mixing within the ERZ between stored 1960s-era magma and at least two new mantle-derived magmas. Lavas from several upper ERZ (UERZ) eruptions in the 1960s and 1970s (including the August 1968 eruption, the Mauna Ulu eruption, and additionally, the eccentric December 1974 eruption near the volcanoâs summit) may each contain at least one component of mantle-derived magma that bypassed the summit reservoir. The early differentiated lavas from the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å rift eruption (1983â2018) were stored in the middle ERZ (MERZ) since the 1960s. This stored magma was rapidly flushed from the ERZ by olivine-controlled 1982-era summit magma, the last of which erupted at PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å by â¼1990. Thereafter, PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas display (1) short-term fluctuations in 206Pb/204Pb on a time scale of <10âyears and (2) a gradual increase in 87Sr/86Sr from â¼0Â·70359 to a maximum of â¼0Â·70364 between â¼2000 and 2003, and a slight decrease thereafter. These mantle-derived isotopic variations were efficiently transmitted from the source to the surface because PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas were poorly buffered by the small volume of magma within the summit reservoir and UERZ to MERZ (â¼0Â·2âkm3, as inferred from a magma mixing trend). An increase in the maximum duration of pre-eruptive magma storage from the UERZ (<7âyr) to the MERZ (<19âyr) and, on average, the more differenatiated nature of downrift lavas is likely controlled by a decrease in the long-term average rate of magma supply to the more distal portions of the ERZ. Our results support recent models for KÄ«laueaâs plumbing system: (1) the summit reservoir comprises two magma bodies; (2) the ERZ is connected to the â¼2â4âkm deep summit magma body beneath the southern rim of the caldera; (3) the volcanic SWRZ is connected to the < 2âkm deep summit magma body beneath the eastern rim of HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u.

INTRODUCTION

The spatial and temporal variations in the composition of lava from active volcanoes provide a detailed view of the number, size, and location of their underlying magma bodies, and the residence time of magma within them (e.g. Cortini & Scandone, 1982; AlbarÃ¨de, 1993; VlastÃ©lic et al., 2007, 2009). KÄ«lauea Volcano, located on the Island of Hawaiâi (Fig. 1), displays systematic variations in lava chemistry on time scales of years to centuries (Fig. 2) due to mantle source heterogeneity and variations in the melting process (e.g. Wright & Tilling, 1980; Hofmann et al., 1984; Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a; Marske et al., 2007; Greene et al., 2013). These mantle-derived changes in the composition of the parental melt delivered to the volcano are subsequently modulated by the transport, mixing, and storage of magma beneath KÄ«laueaâs summit (e.g. Wright, 1971; Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999b; Garcia et al., 2003; Pietruszka et al., 2015) and within its two rift zones (e.g. Wright & Fiske, 1971; Garcia et al., 1989, 1992; Thornber et al., 2015). The interplay of these mantle vs crustal processes at KÄ«lauea is poorly understood. For example, at least nine compositionally distinct batches of mantle-derived magma have been inferred for eruptions at the summit of KÄ«lauea from 1952 to 1982, based on the major element abundances of the lavas (e.g. Helz et al., 2014; Wright & Klein, 2014). However, modeling of the Pb isotope ratios of summit lavas erupted during the late 20th century suggests that only two magma batches are needed (one from 1959 to 1968 and the other from 1971 to 1982), each with a narrow range in 206Pb/204Pb (Pietruszka et al., 2015). The remaining variation in 206Pb/204Pb may be attributed to magma mixing and a short magma residence time (â¼2â3âyears) within the volcanoâs summit magma storage reservoir (Fig. 3).

Lavas from the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å rift eruption (1983â2018) show two cycles in their K2O/TiO2 ratios from 1996 to 2001 (superimposed on a longer-term decreasing trend) that seem to correlate with the inflation and deflation of the volcanoâs summit region (Thornber, 2003). This behavior was interpreted to result from mixing between a compositionally homogeneous PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å-type mantle-derived input magma (with a low K2O/TiO2 ratio) and variable, decreasing amounts of stored 1982-era magma (with a high K2O/TiO2 ratio) from the summit reservoir (Thornber, 2003; Thornber et al., 2015). In contrast, Greene et al. (2013) observed small fluctuations in the 206Pb/204Pb and 208Pb/206Pb ratios of PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas on a time scale of <10âyears (1986 to 2010) that were interpreted to result directly from the melting of filament-shaped compositional heterogeneities (only â¼1â3âkm in diameter) within the Hawaiian mantle plume. These rapid, mantle-derived changes in Pb isotopic composition might be efficiently transmitted from the source to the surface if the parental magmas for the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å eruption partially bypassed the volcanoâs summit reservoir, and avoided its buffering effects (e.g. Garcia et al., 1996). In this study, we use the compositional variations of KÄ«lauea lavas in space and time to better resolve this type of âtop downâ vs âbottom upâ debate (e.g. Thornber, 2003) and investigate the magmatic processes that operate within the plumbing system of this frequently active basaltic volcano.

The architecture of KÄ«laueaâs magmatic plumbing system (Fig. 3) is relatively well understood (e.g. Eaton & Murata, 1960; Tilling & Dvorak, 1993). Primitive magma from the mantle ascends through a primary conduit to KÄ«laueaâs summit reservoir (e.g. Ryan et al., 1981; Klein et al., 1987; Ryan, 1988), which comprises: (1) a â¼2â4âkm deep body beneath the southern rim of the volcanoâs caldera, called the âSouth Calderaâ (SC) magma body; and (2) aâ<â2âkm deep body beneath the eastern rim of HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u (HMM) pit crater, called the HMM magma body (e.g. Fiske & Kinoshita, 1969; Battaglia et al., 2003; Cervelli & Miklius, 2003; Johnson et al., 2010; Baker & Amelung, 2012; Poland et al., 2014; Anderson et al., 2015). The presence of these two magma bodies beneath KÄ«laueaâs summit, possibly holding only â¼0Â·1â0Â·3âkm3 of magma that can readily undergo mixing, is supported by the temporal and spatial variations in the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of summit lavas from 1971 to 1982 (Pietruszka et al., 2015). Magma within the summit reservoir (olivine controlled with >7âwt % MgO since 1959; Wright, 1971; Garcia et al., 2003) is mixed and stored prior to eruption at the summit or lateral intrusion into the East Rift Zone (ERZ) or Southwest Rift Zone (SWRZ) of the volcano (Fig. 4) for further storage, mixing, differentiation and/or eruption (e.g. Wright & Fiske, 1971; Garcia et al., 1989, 1992; Thornber et al., 2003).

The basic model for KÄ«laueaâs plumbing system states that all mantle-derived magma is first delivered from the primary conduit to the summit reservoir before intruding the rift zones via shallow dikes at depths of â¼4âkm or less (e.g. Tilling & Dvorak, 1993; Poland et al., 2014). This idea is consistent with the petrologic monitoring of lavas from the last three decades of the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å ERZ eruption, and since 2008, the compositional similarity between PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas and contemporaneous tephra glasses from the recent lava lake within HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u (Pietruszka et al., 2015; Rowe et al., 2015; Thornber et al., 2015). In detail, however, the magmatic architecture of KÄ«laueaâs rift zones, and their connection to the summit reservoir and the deeper source(s) of melt from the Hawaiian plume, is more complicated. For example, each of the rift zones may consist of two distinct magma pathways (Fig. 3) that radiate from the summit reservoir at different depths (Poland et al., 2014): (1) the âvolcanic SWRZâ and the âHalemaÊ»umaÊ»u-KÄ«lauea Iki Trendâ (HKIT) are < 2âkm deep and fed directly from the HMM magma body; and (2) the classic ERZ (which likely supplied magma to PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å) and the âseismic SWRZâ are â¼2â4âkm deep and fed directly from the SC magma body. Furthermore, studies of ground deformation (e.g. Delaney et al., 1990) and seismicity (e.g. Ryan et al., 1981; Ryan, 1988) suggest that deeper intrusions of magma (down to a depth of â¼9â10âkm) may (at times) allow primitive mantle-derived magma to bypass the summit reservoir on its way to the rift zones. This hypothesis is controversial (e.g. Poland et al., 2014), but it would explain: (1) the presence of two olivine populations, possibly related to magma transport through the ERZ via two different routes, in lavas from the 1969â1974 Mauna Ulu ERZ eruption (Vinet & Higgins, 2010); (2) a wide range in the depth of crystallization (â¼1â16âkm) for olivine crystals (and their CO2-rich melt inclusions) from the 1960 ERZ eruption (Tuohy et al., 2016); (3) the eruption of new magma batches, identified from the major element abundances of the lavas, along the ERZ (as components in hybrid magmas) prior to their eruption at the summit (e.g. Wright & Fiske, 1971; Wright et al., 1975; Wright & Tilling, 1980; Wright & Helz, 1996); and (4) seismic evidence for a deep (â¼8â11âkm) magma body beneath the ERZ (near Mauna Ulu) at the base of the volcanic edifice (Lin et al., 2014).

We present high-precision measurements of the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios, and major and trace element abundances of KÄ«lauea rift zone lavas from 1961 to 2012. These samples represent all of the SWRZ and ERZ eruptions from September 1961 to November 1979 (only the poorly documented March 1980 ERZ eruption is excluded). Published data for PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas (Marske et al., 2008; Greene et al., 2013; Pietruszka et al., 2015), and new analyses of samples from 2006 to 2012, are used to extend this time series. In addition, the Sr and Nd isotope ratios of KÄ«lauea summit lavas from 1959 to 2010 (previously analysed only for Pb isotope ratios by Pietruszka et al. (2015)) are presented. Our approach, based on a detailed comparison of the isotopic composition of contemporaneous rift and summit lavas, is analogous to the studies of Wright (1971) and Wright & Fiske (1971), which used the major element abundances of KÄ«lauea lavas to identify magma batches from the mantle and track them through the summit reservoir and rift zones of the volcano. The major goals of this study are to: (1) establish the petrogenetic relationship between lavas from historical KÄ«lauea summit and rift eruptions (Table 1), based mostly on their Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic compositions; (2) quantify the storage time of magma within the rift zones prior to each eruption (defined as the time elapsed since the emplacement of a given batch of summit-derived magma); (3) identify the components involved in magma mixing (if important) for each rift eruption; and (4) relate these storage times and mixing components to the architecture and evolution of the volcanoâs magmatic plumbing system, with a focus on the rift zones.

ANALYTICAL METHODS

Thirty-two lavas from historical KÄ«lauea rift eruptions, summarized in Supplementary DataTable S1 (supplementary data are available for downloading at http://www.petrology.oxfordjournals.org) were analysed for major and trace element abundances by X-ray fluorescence spectrometry (XRF) at the University of Massachusetts, as described in the Supplementary Data. The XRF results (Supplementary DataTable S2) were used to select a representative subset of 27 samples of glass or rock chips from rift eruptions between September 1961 and November 1979 for isotopic analyses. In addition, 16 PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from 2006 to 2012 and 29 historical KÄ«lauea summit lavas from 1959 to 2010 were analysed for their Sr and Nd isotope ratios [Pb isotopic data for these samples were reported in Greene et al. (2013) and Pietruszka et al. (2015)]. The Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic compositions of the rift (Table 2) and summit (Table 3) samples were measured by: (1) multiple-collector inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry (MC-ICP-MS) at San Diego State University (SDSU) for Pb (by high-precision âTl dopingâ) and Nd (Nu Plasma HR or Nu Plasma 1700); and (2) thermal ionization mass spectrometry (TIMS) at SDSU (VG Sector 54) or the Southwest Isotope Research Laboratories (SWIRL) of the U.S. Geological Survey (USGS) in Denver (Thermo Triton) for Sr. The methods for the isotopic analyses were previously described by Marske et al. (2007), except for the Sr isotopic measurements at the USGS SWIRL (see the Supplementary Data for additional details).

SAMPLING AND OVERVIEW OF HISTORICAL RIFT ERUPTIONS

The historical period of KÄ«lauea Volcano (e.g. Macdonald et al., 1983), defined here as the start of written records in August 1823, was preceded by â¼300âyears of sporadic explosive summit eruptions (starting in â¼1470â1510 CE and recorded by the KeanakÄkoÊ»i Tephra) that culminated with a deadly phreatic eruption in 1790 (e.g. McPhie et al., 1990; Swanson et al., 2012) and a fire-fountaining eruption in â¼1820 (i.e. the âgolden pumiceâ, which likely erupted between 1820 and 1823; Sharp et al., 1987). During the 18th century, possibly in â¼1790 (e.g. Moore & Trusdell, 1991), one or more effusive eruptions (Fig. 4) occurred on the lower ERZ (LERZ, which extends from the prehistoric Heiheiahulu lava shield to the easternmost subaerial tip of the ERZ). From August 1823 to May 1924, the volcanoâs eruptive behavior was dominated by nearly continuous lava lake activity from multiple vents on the floor of KÄ«lauea Caldera before 1868, and from HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u alone thereafter (e.g. Brigham, 1909; Garcia, 2015). Rift eruptions occurred during this period in 1823 (SWRZ), 1840 (ERZ), 1868 (SWRZ), 1877 (ERZ), 1919â1920 (SWRZ, forming the Mauna Iki lava shield), 1922 (ERZ), and 1923 (ERZ).

In May 1924, the lava lake within HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u drained, its floor collapsed, and numerous phreatic explosions occurred. For the remainder of the 20th century (e.g. Garcia, 2015), summit eruptions from the floor of the caldera, KÄ«lauea Iki Crater in 1959 (Fig. 1), or HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u were sporadic (the longest hiatus was from 1934 to 1952) and relatively short (<1âday to a maximum of â¼36âweeks long for the 1967â1968 HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u lava lake activity). Two eruptions on the LERZ in 1955 (â¼13âweeks) and 1960 (â¼5âweeks), the first in this area since 1840, were followed by nine brief (â¼1â15âday long) eruptions (Table 1) along the middle ERZ (MERZ, which extends from NÄpau Crater to Heiheiahulu) and upper ERZ (UERZ, which extends from KeanakÄkoÊ»i to NÄpau Craters) between September 1961 and February 1969 (Fig. 4). Detailed chronologies of these eruptions are presented by Moore & Krivoy (1964), Richter et al. (1964), Fiske & Koyanagi (1968), Wright et al. (1968), Moore & Koyanagi (1969), Jackson et al. (1975), Swanson et al. (1976) and Wright & Peck (1978). The 1969â1974 Mauna Ulu ERZ eruption had two major eruptive phases (May 1969 to October 1971 and February 1972 to July 1974) separated by a 3Â·5-month pause (Swanson et al., 1979; Tilling et al., 1987). During the Mauna Ulu eruption, additional outbreaks of lava on the rift zones occurred from: (1) a discontinuous fissure that started on the floor of the caldera near the edge of HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u and stretched â¼12âkm down the SWRZ for â¼5âdays in September 1971 (Duffield et al., 1982); (2) a series of subparallel fissures between the UERZ near KeanakÄkoÊ»i Crater and the southern part of the caldera in July 1974 (Lockwood et al., 1999); and (3) vents slightly uprift from Mauna Ulu at HiÊ»iaka Crater in May 1973 (<1âday long) and Pauahi Crater from November to December 1973 (lasting â¼4âweeks). Subsequently, an unusual âeccentricâ eruption (<1âday long) from a series of fissures near the volcanoâs summit between the KoaÊ»e fault system (KFS) and the SWRZ in December 1974 (Lockwood et al., 1999) was followed by a â¼3-week eruption along the MERZ in September 1977 (Moore et al., 1980), and a brief (<1âday long) eruption near Pauahi Crater in November 1979. One sample was analysed for its Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic composition from each rift eruption since September 1961, except for Mauna Ulu (nâ=â6) and July 1974 (nâ=â4). In addition, three samples from the December 1974 eruption were analysed for their Sr and Nd isotope ratios to complement the Pb isotopic data of Pietruszka et al. (2015).

The PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å MERZ eruption began in January 1983 (Wolfe et al., 1987), and represents the longest and most voluminous (>4âkm3; Orr et al., 2015) historical rift eruption of KÄ«lauea Volcano. Previous studies (Marske et al., 2007; Greene et al., 2013; Pietruszka et al., 2015) reported high-precision Pb isotopic data for PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from January 1983 to February 2012 (in addition to Sr and Nd isotope ratios for lavas from September 1998 to August 2005 in Marske et al. (2007) and Sr isotope ratios for lavas from January 1983 to January 2010 in Greene et al. (2013)). In this study, PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from January 2006 to February 2012 (nâ=â16, including Menehune) were analysed for their Sr and Nd isotope ratios (the Sr isotope ratios of the samples in common with Greene et al. (2013) were remeasured at SDSU or the USGS SWIRL). A lava lake (the first summit eruption since September 1982) formed within a vent on the floor of HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u (Fig. 1) following a series of small explosions in 2008 (Wilson et al., 2008). This lava lake remained active until May 2018, when it drained rapidly, the eruption of lava at PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å ceased, and a new eruption on the LERZ began near the 1840, 1955, and 1960 vents. At the time of this writing (July 2018), the LERZ eruption continues and volcanic ash is being emitted periodically from a widening and collapsing HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u. A detailed list of the sample locations and eruption dates is presented in Supplementary DataTable S1 for the rift lavas and Pietruszka et al. (2015) for the summit lavas.

RESULTS

Major and trace elements

KÄ«lauea rift lavas display a wide range in MgO with an average value of â¼8âwt % (Fig. 5a) and extend to lower MgO values (5Â·4âwt % in this study) than historical and young prehistoric summit lavas (6Â·0âwt %; Garcia et al., 2003; Marske et al., 2007; Pietruszka et al., 2013). Differentiated lavas with <7âwt % MgO that fractionated clinopyroxeneÂ±plagioclase in addition to olivine (Wright & Fiske, 1971) and olivine-controlled lavas with >7âwt % MgO (Wright, 1971), including both olivine-poor samples with up to â¼10âwt % MgO (e.g. Garcia et al., 1996) and samples that have accumulated olivine (up to the maximum MgO value of â¼14âwt% for this study), have erupted along most of the ERZ. Lavas with <6âwt % MgO are mostly restricted to the MERZ (in September 1977 and rarely during the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å eruption; Garcia et al., 1989; Thornber et al., 2003, 2015) and LERZ (in 1955 and 1960; Wright & Fiske, 1971; Ho & Garcia, 1988; Helz & Wright, 1992; Wright & Helz, 1996). The September 1971 SWRZ lava is olivine controlled (7Â·7âwt % MgO), although some of the most differentiated lavas known from KÄ«lauea (down to 3Â·9âwt % MgO) erupted from or near the SWRZ in prehistoric times (Wright & Fiske, 1971; Anderson & Wright, 1972). Lavas from the eccentric December 1974 eruption are rich in MgO (12Â·1â15Â·7âwt %) and olivine (Lockwood et al., 1999; Garcia et al., 2003). Differentiated lavas make up â¼17% of the total number of samples from KÄ«laueaâs rift zones, excluding the large number of dominantly olivine-controlled PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas. This proportion of differentiated rift lavas is probably an underestimate because no LERZ lavas from 1955 or 1960 were analysed in this study. A significant proportion (â¼33%) of differentiated lavas have also erupted at the volcanoâs summit (Fig. 5b), which confirms (in contrast to early studies; Wright, 1971; Wright & Fiske, 1971) that summit lavas are not strictly olivine controlled (Garcia et al., 2003).

Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic compositions

Lavas erupted over the last millennium at KÄ«laueaâs summit display a systematic fluctuation in their Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic compositions (Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a; Marske et al., 2007). The highest 206Pb/204Pb and lowest 87Sr/86Sr ratios are observed in summit lavas from the early 20th century (Fig. 2). Between 1919 and 1929, probably after the collapse of the HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u lava lake in 1924, the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of summit lavas shifted to lower and higher values, respectively (Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a). This shift is illustrated by the different 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the 1919 and 1959 summit lavas. For the rest of the 20th century (1961 to 1982), the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of summit lavas decreased, whereas their Sr isotope ratios varied only slightly. PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from 1986 to 2012, after the early period of magma mixing within the ERZ (Garcia et al., 1992), continue these trends: (1) a temporal decrease in 206Pb/204Pb followed by cyclic variations over a narrow range on a time scale of <10âyears (Greene et al., 2013); and (2) a gradual increase in 87Sr/86Sr to a maximum of â¼0.70364 between â¼2000 and 2003 and a slight decrease thereafter (Marske et al., 2008; Greene et al., 2013). Tephra glasses from HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u in 2009 and 2010 (Table 3) record the lowest 206Pb/204Pb (18.39â18.40) and highest 87Sr/86Sr (0Â·70361â0Â·70362) ratios for summit lavas since the early 19th century (Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a). The Pb and Sr isotope ratios of rift lavas (Fig. 2) may be either: (1) broadly similar to (e.g. the 1960s, 1970s, and 2010â2012 PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å) or (2) distinct from (e.g. the September 1977 ERZ lava and early PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from 1983 to 1985) contemporaneous summit lavas. These isotopic similarities and differences are the major focus of this study.

Compared to the UwÄkahuna Bluff lavas, most historical KÄ«lauea lavas have lower 87Sr/86Sr ratios (Fig. 7a), similar ÎµNd values (Fig. 7b), and higher Pb isotope ratios (Fig. 7c and d). On plots of 206Pb/204Pb vs208Pb/204Pb or 207Pb/204Pb, summit and rift lavas lie along tight arrays, except for: (1) the lower 208Pb/204Pb at a given 206Pb/204Pb of the 1919 summit lava; (2) three PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas (erupted on 7-Sep-98, 13-Feb-99, and 19-Jun-99) from Greene et al. (2013) with anomalously high 207Pb/204Pb and 208Pb/204Pb (at a given 206Pb/204Pb) that were not observed in two of the same samples analysed by Marske et al. (2008); (3) another PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lava erupted in April 1983 (KE3-117) from Greene et al. (2013) with high 207Pb/204Pb (at a given 206Pb/204Pb); (4) high 207Pb/204Pb (at a given 206Pb/204Pb) for ERZ lavas from August 1963 (DPH-77) and July 1974 (J1974-EV); and (5) low 207Pb/204Pb and 208Pb/204Pb (at a given 206Pb/204Pb) for the 2010 HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u tephra glasses. These observations based on the Pb-Pb diagrams are discussed further in the Supplementary Data. Overall (Fig. 7a), KÄ«lauea lavas display a broad negative correlation on a plot of 206Pb/204Pb vs87Sr/86Sr (the âKÄ«lauea best-fit lineâ), although samples from the mid- to late-20th century show a positive correlation. THE MAGMA BATCH HYPOTHESIS

Olivine-controlled KÄ«lauea lavas from historical summit eruptions display small differences in their SiO2, CaO, K2O, and TiO2 abundances at a given MgO (e.g. Wright, 1971) that are thought to result from short-term changes in the composition of the parental magma delivered to the volcanoâs summit reservoir (e.g. Garcia et al., 2003). Based on these observations, the classic âmagma batchâ hypothesis for KÄ«lauea states that individual batches of compositionally distinct magma from the mantle are tapped by each summit eruption, and that summit eruptions tend to end when a particular magma batch has been exhausted (e.g. Wright & Fiske, 1971; Wright & Klein, 2014). The magma batch hypothesis is illustrated by a Nb/YâK2O/TiO2 diagram (Fig. 6b), where summit lavas plot in distinct fields that vary systematically as a function of eruption date. On this plot, for example, each of the three contemporaneous groups of chemically similar summit and rift lavas may (in principle) have been derived from the same magma batch (i.e. three magma batches, corresponding to the 1960s, the 1970s, and 2010â2012 PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å). In contrast, the September 1977 ERZ lava and early PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from 1983 to 1985 must have at least one component of magma that is chemically distinct from the nearly contemporaneous 1982 summit lavas. Based on their broad similarity to the 1961 and 1967â1968 summit lavas, this additional magma component is most likely summit-derived magma that was stored in the ERZ since the 1960s.

A detailed eruption-by-eruption comparison of the major element abundances of both olivine-controlled and differentiated KÄ«lauea lavas (often including least-squares mass-balance modeling) has been used to identify the transport, mixing, and storage of summit-derived magma batches within the rift zones (e.g. Wright & Fiske, 1971; Wright et al., 1975; Wright & Tilling, 1980; Wright & Helz, 1996). This approach works best for olivine-controlled lavas. However, the major element abundances of many summit and rift lavas (Fig. 5) have been affected (at least slightly) by differentiation beyond olivine control. For example, clinopyroxene(Â±plagioclase) fractionation strongly decreases the CaO/TiO2 ratios of lavas with <7âwt % MgO (Fig. 6c). Multiphase crystal fractionation has clearly modified the chemistry of the September 1977 ERZ lava and the most evolved lavas from the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å eruption (based on their low CaO/TiO2 ratios), but it may have cryptically affected the whole-rock major element abundances of nominally olivine-controlled lavas with >7âwt % MgO if olivine was subsequently added to a differentiated magma. This type of cryptic process is suggested (for example) by the wide range in CaO/TiO2 for the 1960s rift lavas (â¼3Â·6â4Â·4) despite their relatively high MgO contents (all but one sample have >7âwt % MgO). Crystal fractionation (beyond olivine control) likely complicates the identification of magma batches using the major element abundances of KÄ«lauea lavas. We focus on the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the lavas, which are not affected by magmatic differentiation and have a higher proportion of signal to noise than the major element abundances (at a given MgO value) and incompatible element ratios.

EVALUATION OF CRUSTAL CONTAMINATION

The overall Pb, Sr and Nd isotopic variations of KÄ«lauea lavas (Fig. 7) require the derivation of melt from at least three distinct mantle components within the Hawaiian plume, which is thought to be heterogeneous (e.g. Tatsumoto, 1978; Abouchami et al., 2005; Weis et al., 2011) on a small scale (e.g. Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a; Marske et al., 2007; Greene et al., 2013). However, the potential effects of crustal contamination must be evaluated before the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of KÄ«lauea lavas can be used to identify magma batches from the mantle and track their movement though the ERZ and/or SWRZ.

KÄ«lauea magmas may be contaminated by the Pacific oceanic crust and/or the Hawaiian volcanic edifice. The Pacific oceanic crust may include a variety of materials, ranging from the variably altered mid-ocean ridge basalts and/or gabbros that comprise the Cretaceous igneous basement (which is expected to be depleted in highly incompatible elements like Pb) to marine sediments, ferromanganese (Fe-Mn) nodules, and hydrothermal minerals that may be rich in Pb, Sr, and/or Nd. The Hawaiian volcanic edifice may include: (1) older lava flows from KÄ«lauea and/or Mauna Loa, which directly underlie the summit region of KÄ«lauea; (2) partially or completely solidified bodies of KÄ«lauea magma (now gabbro) that may contain veins of highly evolved residual melt (or glass, if solidified); and (3) olivine-rich cumulates, which may also contain a small amount of interstitial KÄ«lauea melt (or glass). In the Supplementary Data and Supplementary Data Table S6, each type of contaminant is evaluated in detail as a potential control on the relatively small isotopic shifts that are used to identify and track magma batches. Below, we demonstrate that the overall Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic variations of KÄ«lauea lavas (represented by the best-fit lines on Fig. 7) are not controlled by crustal contamination. This discussion expands on similar conclusions by Pietruszka & Garcia (1999a) using the much larger amount of isotopic data (including high-precision Pb isotope ratios) that are now available for both KÄ«lauea and Mauna Loa lavas.

Assimilation of materials within the Hawaiian volcanic edifice

The strongest evidence for crustal contamination of KÄ«lauea magmas comes from the variable and low Î´18O values of some lavas (down to â¼4Â·6â°) that are most likely caused by interaction between magma and hydrothermally altered country rocks (with Î´18O values of â¼2Â·6â° or less) from KÄ«lauea and/or Mauna Loa (Garcia et al., 1998, 2008). Cannibalization of old KÄ«lauea lavas or gabbros, or olivine cumulatesÂ±trapped melt or glass would probably sample a random mixture of materials with a net isotopic composition similar to the average of KÄ«lauea lavas on Fig. 7 (206Pb/204Pbâ=â18Â·44 and 87Sr/86Srâ=â0Â·70359). This process (if extensive) would dampen the rapid temporal variations in the Pb and Sr isotope ratios of KÄ«lauea lavas, rather than produce the extremes that are observed at UwÄkahuna Bluff and in 1919. It is difficult to explain even the smaller isotopic shifts, such as the one observed immediately after the 1924 explosive eruption of HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u (Fig. 2), by cannibalization. For example, Pietruszka & Garcia (1999a) modeled this post-1924 decrease in 206Pb/204Pb and increase in 87Sr/86Sr due to the contamination of magma within the volcanoâs summit reservoir by highly evolved residual glass in gabbros from stoped country rock following the collapse and enlargement of HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u by â¼0Â·2âkm3 in 1924 (notably, both ratios moved closer to average KÄ«lauea values from 1919 to 1959; Fig. 7a). However, it is much easier to explain these observations (for the reasons outlined in the Supplementary Data) if the post-1924 lavas represent a new parental magma that formed by relatively low degrees of partial melting (based on their higher Nb/Y ratios; Fig. 6a) of a mantle source that is isotopically distinct from the source of the early 20th century summit lavas.

Mauna Loa lavas (e.g. Weis et al., 2011) tend to have lower Pb isotope ratios (with more scatter in 207Pb/204Pb and 208Pb/204Pb at a given 207Pb/204Pb), higher 87Sr/86Sr ratios, and lower ÎµNd values than KÄ«lauea lavas (Fig. 8). Variable assimilation of old Mauna Loa lava flows by a âhigh 206Pb/204Pb KÄ«lauea end-memberâ magma might create the range in the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios of other KÄ«lauea lavas. However, most Mauna Loa lavas are an inappropriate choice for a contaminant because they have 87Sr/86Sr ratios that are too high (Fig. 8a) and ÎµNd values that are too low (Fig. 8b). Even if an optimized Mauna Loa contaminant on the KÄ«lauea best-fit lines is chosen (such as the purple pentagon in Fig. 8), a large amount of bulk assimilation (â¥60% for historical KÄ«lauea lavas) would be required.

Assimilation of materials from the Pacific oceanic crust

Assimilation of materials from the Pacific oceanic crust is probably restricted to a depth of â¥10âkm beneath KÄ«laueaâs summit region, based on estimates for the thickness of a typical Hawaiian volcanic edifice (e.g. DePaolo & Stolper, 1996). This is much deeper than the volcanoâs shallow plumbing system (Fig. 3), which lies at a depth of â¼4âkm or less (e.g. Tilling & Dvorak, 1993; Poland et al., 2014). As long as any assimilation of the Pacific oceanic crust by mantle-derived KÄ«lauea magma occurs within the primary conduit at a depth of >4âkm, the contaminated magma is likely to be first delivered to the summit reservoir before intruding the rift zones. In this case, the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios of the contaminated magma may be used (as if these signatures were derived from the mantle) to identify and track magma batches. This would be the most likely scenario for nearly all KÄ«lauea lavas. However, deeper intrusions of magma may extend to a depth of â¼9â10âkm (Delaney et al., 1990), which would potentially intersect the uppermost portion of the Pacific oceanic crust. If this represents a zone of magma transport that may bypass the summit reservoir, then contaminated magma could erupt directly along the rift zones with Pb, Sr, and/or Nd isotope ratios unlike contemporaneous summit lavas.

The Cretaceous igneous basement that underlies the Island of HawaiÊ»i formed â¤110âMa ago at a mid-ocean ridge spreading center (Waggoner, 1993), and thus, might be represented by the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios (Fig. 9) of young (âfreshâ) Pacific MORB and/or drilled, altered basalts from Site 843 of the Ocean Drilling Program located in the central Pacific Ocean â¼400âkm west of KÄ«lauea (King et al., 1993; Fekiacova et al., 2007). The Pb, Sr, and Nd concentrations of these basalts and associated gabbros are expected to be similar to or lower than lower than KÄ«lauea magmas (Supplementary DataTable S6). Thus, an enormous amount of bulk assimilation of the igneous basement would be required to explain the total range in the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios of KÄ«lauea lavas (Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a). This can probably be reduced only if the process of assimilation is dominated by the addition of low degree partial melts of crystalline gabbros.

Melting of the lower crust (related either to the Hawaiian volcanic edifice or the underlying Cretaceous igneous basement) may be an important process during the late shield to postshield stages of some Hawaiian volcanoes (e.g. Frey et al., 1990; Gaffney et al., 2004; van der Zander et al., 2010), a period of rapidly declining or low magma supply. Few studies (e.g. Hegner et al., 1986; Stille et al., 1986) have explicitly considered the possibility that Hawaiian magmas may originate within or assimilate (in bulk or as a partial melt) the Cretaceous igneous basement during the main shield stage of a Hawaiian volcano, when the rate of magma supply is at a maximum. Most recently, Eiler et al. (1996) suggested that the low Î´18O values of some olivine phenocrysts in Hawaiian shield basalts (all from the so-called âKeaâ spatial trend of volcanoes, which includes KÄ«lauea and Mauna Kea) are related to the assimilation of hydrothermally altered Pacific oceanic crust by mantle-derived Hawaiian magma (also noting, like Tatsumoto (1978), the broad similarity between the Pb isotope ratios of Kea-trend lavas and Pacific MORB). Pietruszka & Garcia (1999a) subsequently argued that the overall variations in the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios of KÄ«lauea lavas could not be explained either by: (1) melting of the ambient upper mantle lithosphere (e.g. Tatsumoto, 1978) or asthenosphere (e.g. Hauri, 1996; Lassiter et al., 1996) beneath HawaiÊ»i or (2) bulk assimilation of the Cretaceous igneous basement (represented either by Pacific MORB or the Site 843 basalts). Instead, the âKÄ«laueaâ isotopic end member with relatively high 206Pb/204Pb and low 87Sr/86Sr ratios and a high ÎµNd value (Fig. 8) most likely results from the melting of a long-term depleted mantle component within the Hawaiian plume (Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a; Pietruszka et al., 2013).

The high-precision Pb isotope ratios of KÄ«lauea lavas (along with their Sr and Nd isotope ratios) relative to Pacific MORB and Site 843 basalts support the interpretation of Pietruszka & Garcia (1999a). The most common 206Pb/204Pb ratios for Pacific MORB, ranging from â¼18Â·0 to 18Â·9 with an average value of â¼18Â·5, overlap with KÄ«lauea lavas (Fig. 9). However, Pacific MORB have (on average) lower 208Pb/204Pb (Fig. 9a), and especially, higher 207Pb/204Pb (Fig. 9b) ratios than KÄ«lauea lavas (at a given 206Pb/204Pb), and the KÄ«lauea best-fit line on each Pb-Pb diagram is shallower than the array for Pacific MORB. Furthermore, the best-fit trend of KÄ«lauea lavas is strongly orthogonal to the Pacific MORB array on plots of 206Pb/204Pb vs ÎµNd (Fig. 9c and d) or 87Sr/86Sr (Fig. 9e and f). This divergence eliminates the (already remote) possibility that the overall variations in the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios of KÄ«lauea lavas are related to the assimilation of the Cretaceous igneous basement or melting of the ambient mantle lithosphere or asthenosphere beneath HawaiÊ»i, if any of these components may be accurately represented by Pacific MORB.

The Cretaceous igneous basement has probably been altered by seawater and/or hydrothermal fluids and, thus, might be better represented by the Site 843 basalts (King et al., 1993; Fekiacova et al., 2007). These samples (all of which were acid leached prior to digestion in the laboratory, and thus, probably under-represent the extent of post-eruptive alteration) trend towards higher 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios than most Pacific MORB with similar 207Pb/204Pb and 208Pb/204Pb ratios and ÎµNd values (Fig. 9). Post-eruptive alteration of the Site 843 basalts is the most likely cause of the elevated 206Pb/204Pb (due to variable U enrichment of the rock during alteration and post-eruptive decay of the 238U over â¼110âMyr) and 87Sr/86Sr (due to direct alteration of the rock with radiogenic Sr from seawater) ratios (Fekiacova et al., 2007). The most altered Site 843 basalts could serve as an approximate contaminant of KÄ«lauea magmas (as defined by the best-fit lines), at least with respect to the plots of 206Pb/204Pb vs207Pb/204Pb (Fig. 9b) or (roughly) 87Sr/86Sr (Fig. 9f). However, their 208Pb/204Pb ratios are too low (Fig. 9a) and ÎµNd values are (probably) too high (Fig. 9d) to represent either a potential bulk (basaltic) or partially melted (gabbroic) contaminant. These observations exclude the possibility that bulk assimilation of the altered Cretaceous igneous basement (if accurately represented by the most altered Site 843 basalts) controls the overall variations in the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios of KÄ«lauea lavas.

Marine sediments (e.g. pelagic clay, chert, and carbonate), FeâMn nodules (or crusts), and hydrothermal minerals (mainly sulfides and sulfide-rich sediments) are important, but volumetrically minor, components of the Pacific oceanic crust (Fig. 9). Neither marine sediments nor FeâMn nodules are appropriate contaminants to create the overall variations in the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios of KÄ«lauea lavas because both of these materials: (1) have high 208Pb/204Pb (Fig. 9a), and especially, 207Pb/204Pb (Fig. 9b) at a given 206Pb/204Pb, and lie completely above the KÄ«lauea best-fit line on each PbâPb diagram; and (2) have ÎµNd values and 87Sr/86Sr ratios that are orthogonal to the trend of KÄ«lauea lavas on plots of 206Pb/204Pb vs ÎµNd (Fig. 9c) or 87Sr/86Sr (Fig. 9e). The average 206Pb/204Pb and 208Pb/204Pb ratios of hydrothermal minerals (representing the most likely isotopic composition for this potential contaminant) are similar to the high 206Pb/204Pb KÄ«lauea end-member, but their average 207Pb/204Pb (â¼15Â·54) is far too high to explain the overall trend of KÄ«lauea lavas on the 206Pb/204Pbâ207Pb/204Pb diagram (Fig. 9b).

We conclude that crustal contamination of mantle-derived KÄ«lauea magmas by the Hawaiian volcanic edifice or the Pacific oceanic crust does not control the overall Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic variations of KÄ«lauea lavas. As discussed in the Supplementary Data, even the relatively small isotopic shifts are most likely derived (with the additional effects of magma mixing) from the delivery of compositionally distinct magma batches from the mantle.

MAGMA BATCHES AND THE SUMMIT RESERVOIR OF KÄªLAUEA VOLCANO

Many magma batches have been identified for eruptions at the summit of KÄ«lauea Volcano during the mid- to late 20th century based on the major element abundances of the lavas (e.g. Helz et al., 2014; Wright & Klein, 2014). For example, nine compositionally distinct batches of mantle-derived magma were inferred from summit lavas erupted in 1952, 1954, 1959, 1961, 1967â1968, 1971, 1974, 1975, and 1982 (Helz et al., 2014), which amounts to one for each eruption. In this section, we summarize an alternative view of the number of magma batches from 1959 to 1982 based on modeling of the temporal mixing trends defined by the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of KÄ«lauea summit lavas (Fig. 10).

KÄ«lauea summit lavas define a single temporal trend of decreasing 206Pb/204Pb ratios from 1959 to 1968 (Fig. 10a) that can be modeled by the progressive mixing of two compositionally distinct magmas within the volcanoâs summit reservoir (both the HMM and SC bodies, which were probably well connected during this period). This magma mixing trend can be explained if a new batch of mantle-derived magma with a relatively low and constant 206Pb/204Pb ratio of â¼18Â·49â18Â·50 was first delivered to the summit reservoir between 1959 and 1961 (#1 on Fig. 10a), and continuously mixed with the resident magma (initial 206Pb/204Pb ratio of â¼18.60) until 1968. From 1971 to 1982, KÄ«lauea summit lavas define two separate trends of decreasing 206Pb/204Pb ratios (Fig. 10b). During this period, summit eruptions occurred near HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u (September 1971, September 1974, 1975, and April 1982), on the caldera floor (September 1982), or from fissures that extended from the caldera floor towards the UERZ near KeakakÄkoÊ»i Crater (August 1971 and July 1974). The âupperâ trend with higher 206Pb/204Pb at a given time is defined by one of the lavas from September 1982, and all of the summit lavas that erupted from vents near HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u or the westernmost end of the fissures on the caldera floor in August 1971 and July 1974. The âlowerâ trend with lower 206Pb/204Pb at a given time is defined by two of the lavas from September 1982 and the easternmost summit lavas that erupted in August 1971 and July 1974, either on the floor of the caldera or on the caldera rim northwest of KeakakÄkoÊ»i Crater. Each of the temporal trends in 206Pb/204Pb from 1971 to 1982 can be modeled by the progressive mixing of two compositionally distinct magmas within separate bodies.

The locations of the two magma bodies are inferred to coincide with the two major deformation centers beneath KÄ«laueaâs summit region (Fig. 1): (1) the deeper SC body for the âlowerâ mixing trend; and (2) the poorly connected (since at least August 1971), shallower HMM body for the âupperâ mixing trend (which is thought to receive magma only from the SC body). For example, the âlowerâ trend of magma mixing can be explained if a second batch of mantle-derived magma with a relatively low and constant 206Pb/204Pb ratio of â¼18Â·45â18Â·46 was first delivered to the SC body between 1968 and August 1971 (#2 on Fig. 10a), and continuously mixed with the resident magma (initial 206Pb/204Pb ratio of â¼18.49) until September 1982. The mixing model for the lower-trend lavas gives a best-fit magma residence time of â¼1Â·8â2Â·4âyr (maximum range of â¼1Â·5â2Â·9âyr), which corresponds to a magma volume of â¼0Â·1â0Â·3âkm3 (0Â·09â0.3âkm3 maximum range) for the SC body, assuming a â¼0Â·06â0Â·11âkm3/yr range in the rate of magma supply to the summit reservoir. In contrast, the mixing model for the upper-trend lavas gives a longer best-fit magma residence time of â¼5Â·9â8Â·3âyr (maximum range of â¼3Â·9â20Â·6âyr). This value is poorly constrained because the shallow HMM body was supplied from the deeper SC magma body, which was evolving in its Pb isotopic composition on a similar time scale. Pietruszka et al. (2015) estimated that only â¼0Â·01â0Â·03âkm3/yr of magma was delivered to the HMM body from 1971 to 1982, corresponding to a magma volume of â¼0Â·06â0Â·2âkm3 (â¼0Â·04â0Â·6âkm3 maximum range). This modeling suggests that: (1) as few as two compositionally distinct mantle-derived magma batches were delivered to the summit reservoir from 1959 to 1982 (#1 and #2 in Fig. 10a), instead of the seven batches identified by Helz et al. This interpretation will be refined based on the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of summit and rift lavas since 1959, as shown in Fig. 11.

Two distinct peaks are visible on a histogram of the MgO contents of a larger number of historical and young prehistoric KÄ«lauea summit lavas (Fig. 5b). If the data are divided at â¼8âwt % MgO, a narrower peak can be defined at â¼7âwt % MgO and a wider peak can be defined at â¼10âwt % MgO. The predominance of the narrower peak at â¼7âwt % MgO (representing â¼76% of summit lavas) may result from the thermal and compositional buffering of magma that is âperchedâ at the boundary between olivine control and the multiphase crystallization of olivine and clinopyroxeneÂ±plagioclase (Rhodes, 1988). Although some of the summit lavas with >8âwt % MgO may have accumulated a small amount of olivine, crystal-free KÄ«lauea glasses with relatively high MgO contents (up to â¼9â12âwt %) from prehistoric explosive eruptions (including the KeanakÄkaoÊ»i Tephra) and summit eruptions in â¼1820, 1924, 1959, August 1971, and July 1974 have been discovered (Helz, 1987; Garcia et al., 2003; Helz et al., 2014, Swanson et al., 2014; Helz et al., 2015). A wide range in the MgO contents of these glasses (often found within a single eruption) was interpreted by Helz et al. (2015) to result from the storage of magma at different levels beneath the summit of the volcano (with the high-MgO melts erupting directly from a greater depth). The higher average MgO content of rift lavas (â¼8âwt %; Fig. 5a) compared to the summit lavas that (since at least 1971) are inferred to have tapped the shallower, cooler HMM body (â¼7âwt %; Fig. 5b), supports the idea of Poland et al. (2014) that ERZ lavas are supplied from the deeper, hotter SC body. This model for KÄ«laueaâs summit reservoir (Fig. 3) is used for the remainder of this study, but alternative models are evaluated in the Supplementary Data.

THE VOLCANIC SOUTHWEST RIFT ZONE (1971)

Historical eruptions along KÄ«laueaâs volcanic SWRZ (called simply the âSWRZâ for the remainder of this section) occurred in 1823, 1868, 1919â1920 (Mauna Iki), and September 1971. Lava erupted from a series of fissures in September 1971 that propagated from HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u and the floor of the caldera down the SWRZ (Duffield et al., 1982), ending near the Mauna Iki lava shield (Fig. 4). This eruption represents a simple test of the ability of Pb, Sr, and Nd isotope ratios to track the migration of magma within KÄ«laueaâs plumbing system. The isotopic composition (Fig. 7), and K2O/TiO2 and Nb/Y ratios (Fig. 6b) of the olivine-controlled September 1971 SWRZ lava (7Â·7âwt % MgO) are similar to the September 1971 summit lavas. Notably, the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of the September 1971 SWRZ lava (Fig. 10b) is: (1) nearly identical to contemporaneous summit lavas from the âupperâ Pb temporal trend (i.e. the September 1971 and westernmost August 1971 summit lavas, all of which erupted near HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u); and (2) distinct from the easternmost August 1971 summit lavas, which define the âlowerâ Pb temporal trend at this time. A similar observation holds for the Sr isotope ratios (Fig. 12). The similar 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the September 1971 and westernmost August 1971 summit lavas (t-test #1) are indistinguishable from the September 1971 SWRZ lava (t-test #2). In contrast, the 87Sr/86Sr ratio of the September 1971 SWRZ lava is distinct from the easternmost August 1971 summit lavas at the >95% confidence interval (t-test #3). Thus, the September 1971 SWRZ lava was likely supplied from the shallow HMM body rather than the deeper SC body. This magma may have been transported directly from the HMM body to the SWRZ at a deep level (Fig. 3) and/or it may have been delivered to the SWRZ via a near-surface dike from just beneath HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u (e.g. Duffield et al., 1982; Poland et al., 2014). These observations suggest that the September 1971 SWRZ lavas were derived from the summit reservoir (most likely the HMM body) shortly before the eruption (i.e. little or no pre-eruptive magma storage within the SWRZ). Our logic for the SWRZ, as well as the other summit and rift eruptions, is illustrated in Supplementary Data Fig. S1.

THE UPPER TO MIDDLE EAST RIFT ZONE (1961â1974)

Eruptions of the 1960s

From September 1961 to February 1969, KÄ«lauea experienced nine short-lived (â¤15âday long) eruptions (Table 1) along the UERZ and MERZ (Fig. 4), most of which coincided with deflations of the volcanoâs summit region (Wright & Klein, 2014). These 1960s ERZ lavas have a relatively narrow, 6Â·7â8Â·0âwt % range in MgO (Supplementary DataTable S2), except for the samples from August 1968 (a picrite with 14Â·2âwt % MgO; Jackson et al., 1975) and February 1969 (up to 9Â·6âwt % MgO and â¼6âvol. % olivine phenocrysts; Swanson et al., 1976). The CaO/TiO2 ratios (Fig. 6c) of the 1960s ERZ lavas (3Â·6â4Â·3, excluding the August 1968 picrite) are similar to or lower than lavas from the olivine-controlled 1961 and 1967â1968 summit eruptions (4Â·1â4Â·2), suggesting that some of them may have fractionated clinopyroxene(Â±plagioclase) and/or mixed with a differentiated, rift-stored magma (and, in either case, subsequently accumulated a small amount of olivine). In contrast, the K2O/TiO2 and Nb/Y ratios (Fig. 6b) of the 1960s ERZ lavas (0Â·196â0Â·209 and 0Â·63â0Â·72, respectively) overlap with the 1961 and 1967â1968 summit lavas (0Â·197â0Â·207 and 0Â·64â0Â·72, respectively).

The 1960s ERZ lavas display a scattered temporal decrease in 206Pb/204Pb (with values between the 1961 and 1967â1968 summit lavas; Fig. 13a) that plot within error of or slightly above the magma mixing trend defined by summit lavas from 1959 to 1968 (Fig. 10a). This observation is consistent with the idea (based on major element abundances; Wright & Fiske, 1971) that the 1960s ERZ lavas are mixtures of magmas similar to the 1961 and 1967â1968 summit lavas with a temporal increase in the relative amount of the 1967â1968 type of summit magma. This mixing probably occurred mostly within the summit reservoir between a resident magma similar to the most primitive 1959 KÄ«lauea Iki lavas and a mantle-derived input magma (#1 on Fig. 10a) with a lower 206Pb/204Pb ratio that began entering the summit reservoir between 1959 and 1961 (Pietruszka et al., 2015). The 87Sr/86Sr ratio of this input magma (#1 on Fig. 12) must have been similar to the average of lavas from the 1959 KÄ«lauea Iki eruption in order to explain the relatively constant (and similar) values for the 1961 and 1967â1968 summit lavas, and most of the 1960s ERZ lavas except for the August 1968 picrite (t-tests #4 and #5, and ANOVA #1). The 1960s ERZ lavas that plot above the temporal mixing trend defined by the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of summit lavas were likely removed from the summit reservoir and (1) stored for short periods of time within the ERZ prior to eruption and/or (2) mixed with one or more slightly older rift-stored magma(s). Summit-derived magma from the early 20th century (similar to the 1919 summit lava) cannot serve as a mixing component for the 1960s ERZ lavas because its 206Pb/204Pb ratio is too high and its 87Sr/86Sr ratio is too low (Fig. 7a). Thus, KÄ«laueaâs UERZ and MERZ were most likely primed with a large amount of 1960s-era summit-derived magma by the end of the decade.

August 1968 eruption

The August 1968 picrite, which initially erupted from HiÊ»iaka Crater on the UERZ (Jackson et al., 1975), is unusual because it has a slightly lower 87Sr/86Sr ratio (Fig. 12) than the 1961 and 1967â1968 summit and other 1960s ERZ lavas at the >95% confidence interval (t-test #6). The Sr isotope ratio of the Aug. 1968 sample (HI68-02) was analysed four times, giving an average 87Sr/86Srâ=â0Â·703566âÂ±â5 (Â±2Ïm). This value is lower than (1) the four lavas from the 1961 and 1967â1968 summit eruptions, which gave an average 87Sr/86Srâ=â0Â·703577âÂ±â2 (Â±2Ïm) for 11 replicate analyses, and (2) the other 1960s ERZ lavas, which also gave an average 87Sr/86Srâ=â0Â·703577âÂ±â2 (Â±2Ïm) for 36 replicate analyses. The slightly elevated 206Pb/204Pb ratio (18Â·521) of the August 1968 picrite (compared to 18Â·503â18Â·508 for the 1967â1968 summit lavas that erupted shortly before it) indicates that this lava must have at least one component of magma that was stored in the ERZ since the mid- to late-1960s (Fig. 10a), hereafter called the âstored 1960s magma componentâ (Fig. 13b). However, an additional magma mixing component is required to explain its low Sr isotope ratio compared to the other lavas from the 1960s.

It is possible that: (1) a new mantle-derived magma with a relatively low 87Sr/86Sr was delivered to the summit reservoir immediately after the end of the 1967â1968 summit eruption (in July 1968), where it mixed with the resident magma; and (2) the magma within the summit reservoir just prior to the August 1968 eruption (now with a lower 87Sr/86Sr) intruded the ERZ and mixed with the stored 1960s magma component to create the August 1968 picrite. However, it is unlikely that even this small shift in 87Sr/86Sr could have occurred in such a short period of time (<2âmonths) due to: (1) the buffering capacity of the estimated â¼0Â·1â0Â·3âkm3 of magma within the summit reservoir during the 1960s (Pietruszka et al., 2015); and (2) the fact that the Sr isotope ratio of the newly mixed magma within the summit reservoir (just before it was withdrawn to the ERZ) would have to be even lower than the August 1968 picrite in order to match its 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios after additional mixing with the stored 1960s magma component (Fig. 13b). Wright et al. (1975) noted that the major element abundances of the August 1968 picrite have an affinity with lavas that would eventually erupt from Mauna Ulu between 1969 and 1971. Indeed, the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the August 1968 picrite are similar to the June 1969 Mauna Ulu lava (Table 2). Thus, an alternative scenario is that a new mantle-derived magma with a low 87Sr/86Sr ratio (#2a on Fig. 12) bypassed the summit reservoir and mixed with the stored 1960s magma component within the ERZ to create the Aug. 1968 picrite.

Mauna Ulu (1969â1974) and other 1970s ERZ eruptions

The Mauna Ulu eruption created a satellite shield on the UERZ (Fig. 4) from two phases of sustained lava effusion (May 1969 to October 1971 and February 1972 to July 1974) separated by a pause of â¼3Â·5âmonths (Swanson et al., 1979; Tilling et al., 1987). Mauna Ulu lavas are mostly olivine controlled (Wright et al., 1975; Wright & Tilling, 1980) with relatively high CaO/TiO2 ratios (Fig. 6c) and MgO contents (8Â·0â11Â·7âwt % for the six samples analysed in this study). The K2O/TiO2 and Nb/Y ratios of Mauna Ulu lavas initially (in June 1969) matched the 1967â1968 summit lavas, whereas most of the subsequent lavas (except for the first sample after the eruptive pause in April 1972, which is intermediate) have lower ratios similar to the easternmost lavas from the August 1971 and July 1974 summit eruptions (Fig. 6b). Similarly, the 206Pb/204Pb (Fig. 10b) and 87Sr/86Sr (Fig. 12) ratios of Mauna Ulu lavas: (1) decreased from June 1969 to April 1971; (2) increased slightly in April 1972 (after the eruptive pause); and (3) decreased again to relatively constant values in April 1973 and April 1974. The 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the following pairs of Mauna Ulu lavas are distinct at the >95% confidence interval (t-tests #7â9): (1) DAS69-3â2 (June 1969) and DAS71-1213â134 (April 1971); (2) DAS71-1213â134 (April 1971) and MU472-32 (April 1972), from before and after the pause; and (3) MU472-32 (April 1972) and MU474-163 (April 1974).

The isotopic variations of Mauna Ulu lavas are best explained by mixing between three magma components (one stored magma from the 1960s and two new mantle-derived magmas). On a plot of 206Pb/204Pb vs87Sr/86Sr (Fig. 13b), the lavas from each phase of the Mauna Ulu (MU) eruption form separate trends (âearly MUâ and âlate MUâ) that intersect between the fields of lavas from the 1961 and 1967â1968 summit eruptions at relatively high 206Pb/204Pbâ=â18Â·526 and 87Sr/86Srâ=â0Â·703574 (based on a linear regression of the data from each trend), which is similar to ERZ lavas from the mid- to late-1960s. This intersection point may represent the average composition of the stored 1960s magma component within the ERZ that was preferentially erupted at the beginning of each phase of the Mauna Ulu eruption in 1969 and 1972 (although never in 100% pure form). Conversely, the Mauna Ulu lavas with the lowest 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios (in April 1971, and from April 1973 to April 1974) may represent the preferential eruption of two new mantle-derived magmas (one for each eruptive phase) that each progressively flushed the stored 1960s magma out of the ERZ. These magmas (identified below) must be new (rather than older magmas stored within the ERZ) because: (1) they have lower 206Pb/204Pb ratios than older KÄ«lauea lavas since the early 20th century (Fig. 2); and (2) their combined 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios, which plot on the lower left side of the mid- to late 20th century trend, are distinct from these older KÄ«lauea lavas (Fig. 7a).

From June 1969 to April 1971, Mauna Ulu lavas trend towards (and beyond) the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the easternmost lavas from the August 1971 summit eruption (Fig. 13b), which were derived from the SC body (Pietruszka et al., 2015). Nine analyses of the April 1971 Mauna Ulu lava gave 87Sr/86Srâ=â0Â·703544âÂ±â5 (Â±2Ïm), which is similar to the four analyses of the two easternmost August 1971 summit lavas at the Â±2Ïm level (87Sr/86Srâ=â0Â·703550âÂ±â1). Thus, the new magma for the early MU trend (#2a in Fig. 13c) may have been contemporaneous magma from the SC body. However, the 87Sr/86Sr ratios of these two groups of samples are distinct at the â¼95% confidence interval (t-test #10). In addition, the â¼0.0044 difference in 206Pb/204Pb for these nearly contemporaneous summit (â¼18.4918) and rift (18.4874) lavas is greater than the combined Â±2Ï uncertainty (Â±0.0016) for each sample. These observations suggest that the new mantle-derived magma for the first phase of the Mauna Ulu eruption (with lower 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios than the easternmost August 1971 summit lavas) may have bypassed the summit reservoir on its way to the ERZ, where it mixed with the stored 1960s magma component. The 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the April 1971 Mauna Ulu lava are even more distinct from the (nearly identical) September 1971 and westernmost August 1971 summit lavas that erupted near HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u (t-test #11), which were derived from the HMM magma body (Pietruszka et al., 2015). This larger difference (compared to the broad similarity between the April 1971 Mauna Ulu lava and the easternmost August 1971 summit lavas) is consistent with the suggestion of Poland et al. (2014) that the ERZ is connected to the SC body (rather than the HMM body).

From April 1972 to April 1974, Mauna Ulu lavas trend towards the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the easternmost lavas from the July 1974 summit eruption (Fig. 13b), which were derived from the SC body (Pietruszka et al., 2015). Thus, the new magma for the late MU trend (#2âb in Fig. 13c) may have been contemporaneous magma from the SC body. In April 1972, however, the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of the magma within the SC body would likely have been higher than the easternmost July 1974 summit lavas. For example, Pietruszka et al. (2015) attributed the differences in the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of the easternmost summit lavas from August 1971 and July 1974 to â¼3âyears of progressive magma mixing within the SC body between: (1) a resident magma (equal to the average of the easternmost August 1971 summit lavas); and (2) a single mantle-derived input magma (#2 in Fig. 10a) with a relatively low 206Pb/204Pb ratio. Using this model, the magma within the SC body in April 1972 would have had a 206Pb/204Pb ratio of â¼18Â·4828. If this magma from the SC body (in April 1972) was mixed with the stored 1960s magma component to create the April 1972 Mauna Ulu lava (matching its 206Pb/204Pb ratio of 18Â·4984), the expected 87Sr/86Sr ratio of this hybrid magma would be â¼0Â·703554 (i.e. almost on the early MU trend). Four analyses of the April 1972 Mauna Ulu lava gave 87Sr/86Srâ=â0Â·703563âÂ±â7 (Â±2Ïm), which is (just barely) distinct from the predicted value. If this small distinction is real, the April 1972 Mauna Ulu lava might contain a significant component of mantle-derived magma that bypassed the summit reservoir. It is possible that: (1) this new magma (#2âb in Fig. 13c) with a lower 206Pb/204Pb ratio than #2a (and a similar 87Sr/86Sr ratio) was delivered to the volcano after August 1971 (most likely during the pause in the Mauna Ulu eruption); and (2) this magma bypassed the summit reservoir to serve as a mixing component in lavas from the late MU trend (prior to fully mixing within the SC body). Thus, the Pb and Sr isotope ratios are consistent with the evidence from: (1) seismicity (Ryan et al., 1981; Ryan, 1988); (2) the major element abundances of Mauna Ulu lavas (Wright & Tilling, 1980); and (3) their two distinct populations of olivine (Vinet & Higgins, 2010) that at least some mantle-derived magma may have bypassed the summit reservoir during both phases of this eruption. This summit bypass might be related to a deep (â¼8â11âkm) magma body beneath the ERZ (near Mauna Ulu) at the base of the volcanic edifice (Lin et al., 2014).

A third new mantle-derived magma (#2c in Fig. 13c) is required to account for the high 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the high-MgO (and other) 1982 summit lavas (t-test #12). Thus, at least three mantle-derived magmas were likely delivered to the summit reservoir between 1971 and 1982, instead of the one identified by Pietruszka et al. (2015) based only on the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of summit lavas (#2 on Fig. 10a). In this case, the estimated volume of magma within the SC body during this period (â¼0Â·1â0Â·3âkm3) is probably a maximum. This complication does not affect the suggestion of Pietruszka et al. (2015), based on the spatial and MgO-related differences in 206Pb/204Pb for contemporaneous summit lavas, that the SC and HMM bodies were poorly connected from 1971 to 1982. Indeed, this idea is strengthened by the observation that the 87Sr/86Sr ratios (Fig. 12) of: (1) the westernmost summit lavas in August 1971 and July 1974 and (2) the September 1971 and September 1974 summit lavas that erupted near HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u, all of which were supplied from the HMM body, are (respectively, for the 1971 and 1974 periods) distinct from the easternmost summit lavas in August 1971 and July 1974 (which were supplied from the SC body). This interpretation is supported at the >95% confidence interval by t-tests #13â16.

Lavas from Mauna Ulu in April 1973 and April 1974, and other contemporaneous eruptions along the UERZ in May 1973, November-December 1973 and July 1974 (Fig. 4), have Pb and Sr isotope ratios that are similar to the easternmost July 1974 summit lavas (Fig. 13b), and thus, the expected isotopic composition of the magma within the SC body (given their eruption dates within â¼1âyear of July 1974). The similarity in the 87Sr/86Sr ratios of these lavas is supported by ANOVA #2. Conversely, their 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios (at the >95% confidence interval based on t-tests #17 and #18) are distinct from both the September 1974 and westernmost July 1974 summit lavas, which were supplied from the HMM body (Pietruszka et al., 2015). These ERZ lavas plot within error of (May and November-December 1973, and 1973 and 1974 Mauna Ulu) or slightly above (July 1974 ERZ) the lower temporal trend in 206Pb/204Pb (Fig. 10b). Thus, they may have been derived directly from the SC body at the time of eruption or stored only briefly within the UERZ prior to eruption. Alternately, these ERZ lavas (with the exception of the November-December 1973 lava) may have mixed with a small amount of the stored 1960s magma component because they are displaced to slightly higher 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios than the easternmost July 1974 summit lavas. The small difference in the 87Sr/86Sr ratios of these two groups of samples is significant at the >95% confidence interval (t-test #19). It is also possible that some of the magma that fed the end of the Mauna Ulu eruption (as well as the other UERZ eruptions of 1973 and 1974) continued to bypass the summit reservoir, but this is difficult to discern because the magma within the SC body may have essentially reached the isotopic composition of the input magma by this time (#2âb in Fig. 13c). These observations (like those noted previously for the April 1971 Mauna Ulu lava) are consistent with the suggestion of Poland et al. (2014) that the ERZ is connected to the SC body (rather than the HMM body).

Previous studies of the Mauna Ulu eruption have emphasized the importance of a direct mantle control on the major and trace element chemistry of the lavas, including: (1) ten magma batches produced by discrete episodes of partial melting of the mantle (Wright et al., 1975; Wright & Tilling, 1980); and (2) a â¼20% relative increase in the degree of partial melting (of a homogeneous source) during the first three years of the eruption (Hofmann et al., 1984). However, the Pb and Sr isotope ratios of Mauna Ulu lavas suggest that most of these compositional variations are related to magma mixing within the ERZ. The only direct mantle control on the chemistry of Mauna Ulu lavas is recorded by the shift to lower 206Pb/204Pb ratios from the early to late MU trends (Fig. 13b). A total of â¼0Â·35âkm3 of lava erupted at Mauna Ulu, â¼54% from 1969 to 1971 (Swanson et al., 1979) and â¼46% from 1972 to 1974 (Tilling et al., 1987). Assuming a vesicularity of â¼20%, this corresponds to â¼0Â·3âkm3 of vesicle-free magma. If â¼50% of this volume represents the eruption of the stored 1960s magma component, the remainder (â¼0Â·15âkm3) may be attributed to the eruption of magma from the SC body and/or the new mantle-derived magmas that bypassed the summit reservoir. This volume is similar to the estimated â¼0Â·1â0Â·3âkm3 of magma within the SC body from 1971 to 1982 (Pietruszka et al., 2015), which suggests that magma must have been continuously supplied from the mantle in order to sustain the Mauna Ulu eruption. This interpretation is consistent with the relatively large inflation of the volcanoâs summit region from 1969 to 1974 (Wright & Klein, 2014).

ECCENTRIC DECEMBER 1974 ERUPTION AND THE SEISMIC SOUTHWEST RIFT ZONE

The 6-hour December 1974 eruption (Lockwood et al., 1999) was unusual because it occurred along fissures south of KÄ«laueaâs summit between the KFS and volcanic SWRZ (Fig. 4). Poland et al. (2014) considered this eruption to be the only one from the seismic SWRZ during the volcanoâs historical period, whereas Lockwood et al. (1999) associated it with the direct injection of magma from the ERZ into the typically non-eruptive KFS. The eccentric December 1974 lavas are rich in olivine (with minor clinopyroxene and plagioclase) and MgO (12Â·1â15Â·7âwt %; Lockwood et al., 1999), which (along with their relatively high CaO/TiO2 ratios; Fig. 6c) is consistent with the accumulation of olivine into a magma (or a mixture of magmas) that had never differentiated significantly beyond olivine control. In addition, the lavas extend to higher 87Sr/86Sr and lower 206Pb/204Pb ratios (combined) than any KÄ«lauea lavas that erupted earlier in the 20th century (vertical trend in Fig. 13b), signaling the arrival of a new mantle-derived magma (identified below) to the volcano within the â¼5-month period between the end of the Mauna Ulu eruption and December 1974. For example, the high 87Sr/86Sr ratio of the northernmost December 1974 lava is distinct from the easternmost July 1974 summit lavas at the >95% confidence interval (t-test #20).

At least three different magmas are probably required to explain the isotopic variations of the December 1974 lavas. The northernmost December 1974 lava that erupted closest to the caldera has the highest 87Sr/86Sr ratio of 0Â·703566âÂ±â8 (Â±2Ïm), which is indistinguishable (t-test #21) from the 1982 summit lavas (Fig. 13c). The September 1982 lavas display a significant range in 206Pb/204Pb (at constant 87Sr/86Sr) that correlates with their MgO content (Fig. 10b), possibly due to (incomplete) syn-eruptive mixing between a high-MgO magma (206Pb/204Pbâ=â18Â·455) from the SC body and a low-MgO magma (206Pb/204Pbâ=â18Â·475) from the HMM body (Pietruszka et al., 2015). In December 1974, however: (1) the isotopic composition of magma in the HMM body was probably intermediate between the lavas from the September 1974 and 1975 summit eruptions [206Pb/204Pbâ=â18Â·493 based on the best-fit mixing model of Pietruszka et al. (2015)]; and (2) the isotopic composition of the magma in the SC body was probably intermediate between the easternmost July 1974 and the high-MgO September 1982 summit lavas [206Pb/204Pbâ=â18Â·464 based on the best-fit mixing model of Pietruszka et al. (2015)]. Thus, the northernmost December 1974 lava (with its 206Pb/204Pb ratio of â¼18Â·477) probably does not represent the eruption of contemporaneous magma from either the HMM or SC body alone. A mixture of these magmas with a 206Pb/204Pb ratio of â¼18Â·477 would have a 87Sr/86Sr ratio of â¼0Â·703558, which is within the Â±2Ïm error of the northernmost December 1974 lava. However, there is no known pathway to mix magma from both the HMM and SC bodies, and transport it to the area beneath the vents of the December 1974 lavas (e.g. Poland et al., 2014). Instead, we propose that a new mantle-derived magma with Pb and Sr isotope ratios similar to the high-MgO September 1982 lavas (#2c in Fig. 13c) bypassed the summit reservoir and directly entered the area beneath the December 1974 vents [i.e. the seismic SWRZ based on Poland et al. (2014) and/or the KFS based on Lockwood et al. (1999)]. This 1982-type magma likely served as one of three mixing components for the December 1974 lavas.

This interpretation is supported (indirectly) by the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr (t-test #22) ratios of the olivine-controlled lava from the November 1979 UERZ eruption (Fig. 13b), which are nearly identical to the northernmost December 1974 lava. By 1979, however, mixing within the SC body between an initial resident magma similar to the easternmost August 1971 summit lavas and the mantle-derived 1982-type magma (#2 in Fig. 10a) was nearly complete [206Pb/204Pbâ=â18Â·456 based on the best-fit mixing model of Pietruszka et al. (2015)]. In this case, the November 1979 lava probably represents contemporaneous magma (similar to the high-MgO September 1982 summit lavas, but perhaps with a slightly lower 87Sr/86Sr ratio; Fig. 12) from the SC body (â¼75%) that entered the ERZ and mixed with a smaller amount (â¼25%) of stored magma (Fig. 13c), most likely left over from the Mauna Ulu eruption (itself dominated by the stored 1960s magma component). Thus, the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios of the November 1979 lava (unlike those from December 1974) can be explained by a simple magma mixing scenario that is consistent with the architecture of KÄ«laueaâs plumbing system (e.g. Poland et al., 2014).

A second mixing component (with relatively high 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr) for the December 1974 lavas (Fig. 13c) can potentially be explained by: (1) contemporaneous magma from the HMM body [206Pb/204Pbâ=â18Â·493 based on the best-fit mixing model of Pietruszka et al. (2015), corresponding to a 87Sr/86Sr ratio of â¼0Â·703565]; (2) stored magma from the volcanic SWRZ similar to lavas from the September 1971 eruption; or (3) the stored 1960s magma component. It is impossible to choose between these scenarios based solely on the Pb and Sr isotope ratios of the December 1974 lavas. There are no known pathways to transport magma from either the HMM body or the volcanic SWRZ to the area beneath the vents of the December 1974 lavas, but the seismic SWRZ is thought to be connected to the SC body (e.g. Poland et al., 2014) and a direct injection of magma into the KFS from the ERZ occurred in December 1965 (Lockwood et al., 1999). Thus, it seems most likely that the 1982-type magma bypassed the summit reservoir and mixed with a stored mid- to late-1960s era magma that had previously intruded the KFS (from the ERZ) and/or seismic SWRZ (from the SC body).

The vertical trend of the December 1974 lavas in Fig. 13c requires that this hybrid magma was subsequently mixed with a third magma. This final mixing component (with relatively low 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios) is similar to Mauna Ulu and other UERZ lavas from 1973 and 1974, and the easternmost July 1974 summit lavas. Thus, it can potentially be explained by: (1) contemporaneous magma from the SC body [206Pb/204Pbâ=â18Â·464 based on the best-fit mixing model of Pietruszka et al. (2015), which corresponds to an 87Sr/86Sr ratio of â¼0Â·703552]; or (2) magma that was only briefly stored (since 1973 or 1974) within the ERZ. The two southernmost December 1974 lavas have the lowest 87Sr/86Sr ratios, and thus, must contain the greatest amount of magma from the SC body (scenario #1) or the ERZ (scenario #2). Scenario #1 would require an intrusion of magma from the SC body to the seismic SWRZ, which is consistent with the model of Poland et al. (2014). However, a direct injection of (briefly) stored magma from the ERZ into the KFS may have occurred in May 1973, when magma migrated westward as a shallow dike from the UERZ into the eastern end of the KFS (Lockwood et al., 1999). This shallow dike likely solidified quickly (Davis, 2015), and it is unknown if a deeper pathway exists to transport magma from the UERZ to the western end of the KFS. Nevertheless, scenario #2 is an intriguing possibility to investigate in the future. If the suggestion of Poland et al. (2014) that the December 1974 eruption tapped the seismic SWRZ is correct, scenario #2 would further require that magma from the UERZ can enter the seismic SWRZ via the KFS.

THE PUÊ»U Ê»ÅÊ»O ERUPTION (1983â2018)

The PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å MERZ eruption began on January 3, 1983 after a dike intersected stored magma east of NÄpau Crater (Wolfe et al., 1987). The first outbreak of lava was at NÄpau Crater (Fig. 4), but the eruptive fissures extended â¼6âkm further down the ERZ. The earliest lavas were differentiated (5Â·7â6Â·6âwt % MgO), and most of their compositional variation can be explained by mixing (to create an âearly hybridâ) between a strongly evolved, rift-stored magma similar (or identical) to differentiated lava from the nearby September 1977 MERZ eruption and a less evolved, rift-stored magma (of unknown parentage) that had also differentiated beyond olivine control (Garcia et al., 1989). The September 1977 lava itself likely fractionated from a 1960s-era summit-derived magma (similar to the stored 1960s magma component) based on its 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios (Fig. 14). The early hybrid magma with a low CaO/TiO2 ratio due to clinopyroxene and plagioclase fractionation (the low-MgO end of the dashed red field in Fig. 6c) was gradually flushed from the ERZ by a contemporaneous summit-derived magma with â¼9â10âwt % MgO and a higher CaO/TiO2 ratio typical of olivine-controlled KÄ«lauea lavas (Garcia et al., 1992). The summit-derived magma was first detected in PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from March 1983, and its importance as a mixing component grew continuously (based on a temporal increase in CaO/TiO2) until it reached 100% of the erupted lava in February 1985 (ending the early period of magma mixing within the ERZ; Garcia et al., 1992). Modeling of the increase in CaO/TiO2 suggests that this rapid early mixing occurred within a small (â¼0.05âkm3) magma pocket beneath PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å (Shamberger & Garcia, 2007).

The rate of magma supply during the early years of the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å eruption was estimated to be â¼0Â·11âkm3/yr (Dvorak & Dzurisin, 1993), or â¼0.2âkm3 of magma from January 1983 to September 1984.
