Thus, a substantial amount of 1982-era magma was likely removed from the summit reservoir during the first two years of the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å eruption (a period of continuous summit deflation; Thornber, 2003; Wright & Klein, 2014). Our interpretation for PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from January 1983 to September 1984 based on their Pb and Sr isotope ratiosâthe rift-stored, 1960s-era âearly hybridâ magma was flushed from the ERZ by 1982-era summit magmaâagrees with the conclusions of Garcia et al. (1989,1992) and Thornber (2003).

Garcia et al. (1996) first observed a temporal decrease in the MgO-normalized abundances (e.g. CaO or K2O) and ratios (e.g. La/Yb or Ba/Y) of incompatible elements in olivine-controlled PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas over the decade following the end of the early period of magma mixing within the ERZ. These systematic trends continued into the early 2000s (Garcia et al., 2000; Thornber, 2003; Pietruszka et al., 2006; Marske et al., 2008; Greene et al., 2013; Thornber et al., 2015). The 206Pb/204Pb ratios of PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas (Fig. 15a) decreased rapidly after September 1984 until they reached a minimum plateau of â¼18Â·387âÂ±â2 (Â±2Ï) from August 1988 to October 1990 (Greene et al., 2013). Thereafter, PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas display: (1) short-term fluctuations in 206Pb/204Pb on a time scale of <10âyears (Marske et al., 2008; Greene et al., 2013); and (2) a gradual increase in 87Sr/86Sr to a maximum of â¼0Â·70364 between â¼2000 and 2003, and a slight decrease thereafter (Fig. 15b). The origin of these compositional variations is controversial.

In their âtop downâ model, Thornber (2003) and Thornber et al. (2015) argued that the 1982-era summit magma (with, for example, relatively high 206Pb/204Pb, La/Yb, and K2O/TiO2 ratios) was gradually flushed from the summit reservoir (and semi-isolated pockets within the ERZ) by a new mantle-derived magma with low 206Pb/204Pb, La/Yb, and K2O/TiO2 ratios that is represented by PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from â¼2001. This interpretation may explain the two cycles in the K2O/TiO2 ratios of PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from 1996 to 2001 (superimposed on the longer-term decreasing trend) that seem to correlate with the inflation and deflation of the volcanoâs summit region (Thornber, 2003). The 2008â2010 tephra glasses from HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u and contemporaneous PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas are compositionally (Rowe et al., 2015; Thornber et al., 2015; Fig. 6) and isotopically (Fig. 15) similar. This observation suggests that, as of at least 2008, the remaining 1982-era magma within the summit reservoir had been completely replaced by âmodernâ PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å-type magma (Rowe et al., 2015; Thornber et al., 2015). Thornber et al. (2015) emphasize the long-term compositional homogeneity of this PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å-type magma, and [along with Rowe et al. (2015)] suggest that the 1982-era magma was finally removed from the plumbing system during the surge of mantle-derived magma from 2003 to 2007 (Poland et al., 2012). In summary, the âtop downâ model accounts for all of the compositional variations of PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from mid-1984 to 2007 (beyond the effects of crystal fractionation and accumulation) by two-component mixing between a 1982-era summit magma (stored in the summit reservoir and the ERZ) and a new mantle-derived PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å-type magma (similar to lavas from â¼2001) that did not vary significantly in composition.

Alternately, we interpreted the chemical and isotopic variations of PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas (after the end of the early period of magma mixing within the ERZ) to result mostly from a dynamic process of melting small-scale mantle heterogeneities within the Hawaiian plume. This view was characterized as a âbottom upâ model by Thornber (2003). Modeling of the temporal decrease in the ratios of incompatible elements and 226Ra-230Th-238U disequilibria from 1985 to 2001 suggests that PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas were increasingly derived from a mantle source that was recently depleted by prior melt extraction within the last â¼8âkyr (Pietruszka et al., 2006). The mantle source region of PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas must also contain ancient, small-scale compositional heterogeneities based on the temporal variations in the 206Pb/204Pb and 87Sr/86Sr ratios (Fig. 15). These variations in lava chemistry at PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å were inferred to result from a single magmatic processâthe direct transfer of melt from pores in steady-state equilibrium with the mantle into chemically isolated channels (Pietruszka et al., 2006). When melt is extracted into channels to supply a sustained eruption (such as Puâu âÅâÅ), it must be drained from an ever-increasing volume of mantle in order to sustain the flow of melt to the surface. As the eruption continues, the volcano might tap melt from more distal areas and tend to sample: (1) additional melt from recently depleted mantle; and (2) chemically and isotopically distinct melt from âfreshâ mantle that never before melted beneath HawaiÊ»i.

These rapid, mantle-derived changes in lava chemistry were thought to be efficiently transmitted from the source to the surface because PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å magma partially bypassed KÄ«laueaâs summit reservoir, and avoided its buffering effects (Garcia et al., 1996). The evidence for this idea is based on a residence time analysis of the variations in lava chemistry. For example, the rate of change in Ba/Y for PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from 1985 to 1992 was a factor of â¼3 faster than observed for summit lavas over the previous 200âyears (Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999a). Accordingly, Garcia et al. (1996) suggested that PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å magma avoided mixing with the magma in the summit reservoir, providing a more direct âwindowâ to the mantle than summit lavas. However, this interpretation relied on the inference that the summit reservoir held â¼2â3âkm3 of magma during the late 20th century (Pietruszka & Garcia, 1999b), which is now thought to be a factor of â¼10 too large (Pietruszka et al., 2015). Thus, we revisit our previous modeling and interpretations.

We applied the residence time model of Pietruszka et al. (2015) to the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from September 1984 (i.e. after the early period of magma mixing was essentially complete) to October 1990. The model assumes that the temporal decrease in 206Pb/204Pb (Fig. 15a) results from mixing between: (1) a resident magma with a relatively high initial 206Pb/204Pb ratio (=18Â·442, based on the September 1984 lava); and (2) a mantle-derived input magma with a lower 206Pb/204Pb ratio (=18Â·387, based on the average of PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from August 1988 to October 1990). Using the full range in model parameters given by Pietruszka et al. (2015), the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of these PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas are best matched by a residence time of â¼1Â·6â2Â·1âyears and a magma volume of â¼0Â·2âkm3 (assuming a magma supply rate of â¼0Â·11âkm3/yr; Dvorak & Dzurisin, 1993), which likely represents the amount of magma that was undergoing mixing within both the summit reservoir and the UERZ to MERZ. Thus, there is no need to call upon a summit bypass for the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å eruption. Instead, the temporal decrease in 206Pb/204Pb probably results mostly from magma mixing within the summit reservoir, and the nearly constant transfer of this continuously mixed magma from the SC body to PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å. This interpretation suggests that both summit lavas and lavas from sustained rift eruptions provide a âwindowâ to the mantle beneath KÄ«lauea, as long as the time scale of the variation in lava chemistry is significantly greater than the typical residence time of magma within the summit reservoir (â¼2â3âyr). âTop downâ crustal (mixing-related) magmatic processes dominate on shorter times scales (except for rift lavas that bypass the summit reservoir), whereas âbottom upâ mantle (source- and melting-related) magmatic processes dominate on longer time scales. All of our previous interpretations of mantle processes at PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å rely on variations in lava chemistry that span more than â¼2â3âyr.

The critical 206Pb/204Pb ratio of magma within the SC body in September 1982 (â¼18Â·455) may be used to estimate the amount of 1982-era summit magma that erupted at PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å after September 1984. On a plot of 206Pb/204Pb vs87Sr/86Sr, PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from September 1984 to October 1990 are distinct from the 1982 summit lavas (Fig. 14) and older KÄ«lauea lavas since the early 20th century (Fig. 7a). This observation (along with the result of the residence time model) suggests that a new mantle-derived magma with a low 206Pb/204Pb ratio of â¼18Â·387 was delivered to the summit reservoir before September 1984 (when the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas first declined below the critical value). Based on the average of PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from August 1988 to October 1990, the 87Sr/86Sr ratio of this magma was â¼0Â·703589. This isotopically distinct melt delivery from the mantle must have occurred after the September 1982 summit eruption (Pietruszka et al., 2015), and it may have coincided with the start of the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å eruption in January 1983. It probably did not erupt at PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å (in âpureâ form) until August 1988 (the initial minimum in 206Pb/204Pb) because it first had to flush the rest of the 1982-era summit magma from the plumbing system (via the ERZ). From September 1984 to August 1988, â¼0Â·4âkm3 of magma was supplied to PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å (assuming a rate of â¼0Â·11âkm3/yr; Dvorak & Dzurisin, 1993). If â¼50% of this volume represents the new mantle-derived magma, the remainder (â¼0Â·2âkm3) can be attributed to the rest of 1982-era summit magma. Thus, the total amount of 1982-era summit magma that erupted at PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å is inferred to be â¼0Â·3âkm3 (i.e. â¼0Â·1âkm3 before mid-1984 and â¼0Â·2âkm3 from mid-1984 to August 1988). This volume is similar to the estimated â¼0Â·1â0Â·3âkm3 of magma within the SC body from 1971 to 1982 (Pietruszka et al., 2015) and the estimated â¼0Â·2âkm3 of magma undergoing mixing within the summit reservoir and the UERZ to MERZ from September 1984 to October 1990.

Our revised interpretation for PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from September 1984 to October 1990 based on their Pb and Sr isotope ratiosâthe remaining 1982-era magma was flushed from the summit reservoir (via the ERZ) by a new mantle-derived magma similar to PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas from August 1988 to October 1990âagrees with the conclusions of Thornber (2003) and Thornber et al. (2015). The remaining controversy relates to the: (1) the persistence of 1982-era magma within the plumbing system; and (2) the possibility that the mantle-derived PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å-type magma entering the summit reservoir has varied in composition. All PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas since 1986 plot on a vertical trend of 206Pb/204Pb vs87Sr/86Sr that does not intersect the 1982 summit lavas (Fig. 14). This observation is inconsistent with the two-component mixing scenario predicted by the âtop downâ model. The 1982-era magma (regardless of its storage location) ceased to be a significant mixing component in PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas by August 1988, when the minimum 206Pb/204Pb ratio was reached (Fig. 15a) and the 87Sr/86Sr ratios began to increase (Fig. 15b). Models that call upon the extended residence of 1982-era magma within the summit reservoir, possibly until the 2003â2007 magma surge (Thornber, 2003, Rowe et al., 2015, Thornber et al., 2015), are likely to be incorrect.

The isotopic variations of PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas (on a time scale of >2â3âyr) after â¼1990 (Marske et al., 2008; Greene et al., 2013) are interpreted to result mostly from dynamic mantle processes [e.g. the melt extraction model of Pietruszka et al. (2006)]. For example, the <10-yr cycles in the Pb isotope ratios of PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas (Fig. 15a) may result from the melting of a fine-scale repeating pattern of filament-shaped compositional heterogeneities (only â¼1â3âkm in diameter) in the mantle source region (Greene et al., 2013). Similarly, the vertical trend towards high 87Sr/86Sr ratios for PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas can be explained (Fig. 8a) if KÄ«laueaâs typical pathways of melt extraction migrated slightly towards Mauna Loa, where a mixture of both KÄ«lauea- and Mauna Loa-like mantle components (as â¼2â4âkm wide blobs) might exist (Marske et al., 2008). Our interpretation for PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas since â¼1990 based on their Pb and Sr isotope ratiosâthe composition of melt extracted from KÄ«laueaâs source region within the Hawaiian plume varied almost continuously, and thus, the related fluctuations in lava chemistry provide a âwindowâ to the mantleâis inconsistent with that idea that the composition of the mantle-derived PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å-type magma delivered to the summit reservoir remained constant until â¼2007 (Thornber, 2003; Thornber et al., 2015). The apparent correlation between the K2O/TiO2 ratios of PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas and the deformation of the volcanoâs summit region (Thornber, 2003) might be related to the delivery of these compositionally distinct magma batches from the mantle.

MODELING OF MAGMA STORAGE TIMES FOR LATE 20TH CENTURY ERUPTIONS

The three mixing trends defined by the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of KÄ«lauea summit lavas from 1959 to 1982 can be used to infer the pre-eruptive magma storage times of contemporaneous rift lavas. These estimates are based on a comparison between the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of a given rift lava with the model results of Pietruszka et al. (2015) for each of the three summit mixing trends (Fig. 10a): (1) 1959 to 1968; (2) the upper trend from 1971 to 1982 for lavas from the HMM body; and (3) the lower trend from 1971 to 1982 for lavas from the SC body. We determined the time when the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of each rift lava (either before, on, or after its eruption date) would lie on each of 20 model permutations of the appropriate mixing trend (see Supplementary DataTable S7 for the individual results). For each model permutation, this time is subtracted from the eruption date (both expressed in years since the start of the mixing trend) to estimate a characteristic time, T. Positive values for T (when the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of the rift lava is higher than the predicted value for contemporaneous summit magma, but similar to the inferred value for older summit magma) reflect the duration of magma storage within the rift zone. Negative values for T (when the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of the rift lava is lower than the predicted value for contemporaneous summit magma, but similar to the inferred value for future summit magma) reflect magma that may have bypassed the summit reservoir on its way to the rift zone.

The uncertainty in T related to the summit mixing trends is difficult to quantify. The 20 model permutations for each of the three summit mixing trends are thought to represent the reasonable extremes of the model parameters that will match the 206Pb/204Pb ratios of the summit lavas (Pietruszka et al., 2015), and thus, the greatest potential range in T for a given rift lava. Accordingly, we report the average value for T (Â±2Ï, when appropriate) for each rift lava based on the model permutations (Table 4). In addition, a non-zero value for T was accepted only when the 206Pb/204Pb ratio of a given rift lava was different from the predicted 206Pb/204Pb ratio for contemporaneous summit magma by at least Â±4Ï (Â±0Â·0031) based on a majority of the model permutations. Otherwise, the rift lava is assumed to have a storage time of â¼0âyr.

The UERZ lavas were probably stored for the shortest periods of time prior to eruption, ranging from â¼0 to 7Â·0âyr based on the model results (Fig. 16a). The UERZ, based on its proximity to the primary conduit and summit reservoir (Fig. 3), probably experiences a higher long-term average rate of magma supply than the rest of the ERZ (at least, prior to the start of the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å eruption in 1983 and the new LERZ eruption in 2018).

Lavas from several eruptions along the UERZ in the 1960s and 1970s (especially August 1968 and 1969â1974 Mauna Ulu) and the seismic SWRZ or KFS in December 1974 may each have at least one component of mantle-derived magma that bypassed the summit reservoir. Notably, the lavas from each of these three eruptions are relatively mafic [â¼8Â·0â14Â·2âwt % MgO in this study and Garcia et al. (2003)] and rich in olivine (Lockwood et al., 1999; Garcia et al., 2003; Vinet & Higgins, 2010). There is no evidence that any magma bypassed the summit reservoir and directly entered either the MERZ or volcanic SWRZ.

SYNTHESIS

The magmatic evolution and architecture of the rift zones of KÄ«lauea Volcano since the mid-20th century is summarized using: (1) the magmatic processes and mixing components (Fig. 11) based on the Pb and Sr isotope ratios of the lavas; and (2) the magma storage times (Table 4). Our interpretations are illustrated using a time series of schematic cross sections through the summit and rift zones of the volcano (Fig. 17). For simplicity, these cross sections depict magma within the rift zones as single dikes.

Fig. 17.
Open in new tabDownload slide

The magmatic evolution and architecture of the summit and rift zones of KÄ«lauea Volcano from 1959 to early 2018, illustrated using a time series of schematic cross sections.

A magma batch from the mantle (input magma #1 in Fig. 17a) was delivered to KÄ«laueaâs summit reservoir just before, during, or shortly after the 1959 KÄ«lauea Iki eruption. The resident magma within the summit reservoir (initially similar to the 1959 summit lavas) progressively mixed with this input magma until 1968. The HMM and SC bodies were well connected at this time. A series of intrusions from the summit reservoir to the ERZ in the 1960s (often leading to eruptions along the UERZ and MERZ) left one or more relatively large pockets of magma (Fig. 17b) to serve as a prominent mixing component in subsequent rift lavas (up to, and including, the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å eruption). This 1960s-era magma, represented by the stored 1960s magma component in Fig. 13, also intruded the seismic SWRZ. The 1960s rift lavas (except the August 1968 picrite) were stored in the ERZ for short periods of time prior to eruption (â¼0 to 3Â·8âyr). The August 1968 magma was stored for several years prior to mixing with a new mantle-derived magma (input magma #2a in Fig. 17b) that bypassed the summit reservoir.

Between 1968 and 1971, this magma batch (input magma #2a in Fig. 17c) began to enter the SC body, which became partially disconnected from the HMM body. This separation may have been related to the initiation of the Mauna Ulu eruption in 1969. Another new magma batch from the mantle (input magma #2b in Fig. 17d) was delivered to the volcano between 1971 and 1972, most likely ending the pause in the Mauna Ulu eruption. Mauna Ulu lavas from 1969 to 1971 (early MU) and 1972 to 1974 (late MU) record progressive mixing (in the ERZ) between each of these magma batches (#2a and #2b, respectively, for each eruptive phase) and the stored 1960s magma component. The two new magma batches for the Mauna Ulu eruption may have been transported to the ERZ via the SC body and/or they may have bypassed the summit reservoir.

Mauna Ulu lavas from 1971, 1973, and 1974, and lavas from other ERZ eruptions in May 1973, November-December 1973 and July 1974, are similar to contemporaneous summit lavas from the SC body. In contrast, lava from the September 1971 eruption on the volcanic SWRZ is nearly identical to contemporaneous summit lavas erupted near HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u, suggesting that it tapped the HMM body immediately before or during the eruption. Thus, the ERZ is connected to the SC body (Fig. 17d) and the volcanic SWRZ is connected to the HMM body (Fig. 17c). The duration of magma storage within the ERZ for Mauna Ulu lavas from 1973 and 1974, and lavas from May 1973, November-December 1973, and July 1974 was short (â¼0â1Â·6âyr). Lavas from the eccentric December 1974 eruption, supplied by a mixed magma that was stored within the seismic SWRZ and/or the KFS for a few years, contain a component of new mantle-derived magma that bypassed the summit reservoir (input magma #2c in Fig. 17d). This magma batch was also delivered to the summit reservoir, where it progressively mixed with the resident magma until (at least) September 1982. The November 1979 ERZ lava is a mixture of this magma from the SC body (after it had nearly reached the composition of input magma #2c) and a mixed, rift-stored magma (Fig. 17e) that was left over from the Mauna Ulu eruption (itself dominated by the stored 1960s magma component).

In 1983, the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å eruption initially tapped a strongly evolved, rift-stored magma similar (or identical) to differentiated lava from the nearby September 1977 ERZ eruption. The September 1977 lava itself likely fractionated from an older magma that was derived from the summit reservoir in the mid- to late-1960s (Fig. 17e). The early PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å magma was rapidly flushed from the ERZ by 1982-era magma from the SC body. This 1982-era summit-derived magma was itself flushed from the plumbing system by a new mantle-derived magma that was delivered to the summit reservoir between 1982 and 1984 (most likely coinciding with the start of the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å eruption). This magma batch finally erupted in âpureâ form at PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å from â¼1988 to 1990. Thereafter, the composition of melt extracted from KÄ«laueaâs source region within the Hawaiian plume has varied almost continuously. These mantle-derived changes in lava chemistry were efficiently transmitted from the source to the surface (via the SC body) because the parental magmas for the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å eruption were poorly buffered by the small volume (â¼0.2âkm3) of magma within the summit reservoir and UERZ to MERZ (Fig. 17f). The similarity of the 2008â2010 tephra glasses from HalemaÊ»umaÊ»u and contemporaneous PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å lavas indicate that the HMM and SC bodies were (again) well connected at this time (and probably until at least April 2018). The current state of KÄ«laueaâs magmatic plumbing system is unknown.

BROADER IMPLICATIONS

The chemical and isotopic signatures of basalts from mid-ocean ridge and ocean-island volcanoes are frequently used to reconstruct the origin and length scale of mantle heterogeneity, and the process of basaltic melt generation and transport. Many studies have demonstrated that melt or magma mixingâstarting with the inception of melting in the mantle and ending with the amalgamation of magma batches in crustal reservoirs (with simultaneous crystallization, and possibly, assimilation)âmodifies the primary compositional signals from the mantle (e.g. Reiners, 2002; Maclennan, 2008; Rubin et al., 2009; Stracke & Bourdon, 2009; Shorttle et al., 2016). In this study, we have deciphered the final stages of the complex and dynamic process of crustal magma mixing for KÄ«lauea Volcano since 1959. Our detailed analysis of the Pb and Sr isotope ratios of contemporaneous summit and rift lavas on an eruption-by-eruption basis has provided a first-order constraint on the timing and composition of melt deliveries from the mantle (Fig. 11) to KÄ«laueaâs magmatic plumbing system (Fig. 17).

The residence time of magma within KÄ«laueaâs summit reservoir (typically â¼2â3âyears since the mid-20th century) is similar to or shorter than the time scale for the delivery of these compositionally distinct magma batches (<5â10âyr per batch, but perhaps <1â2âyr, as revealed when magma bypasses the summit reservoir). The duration of magma storage within the SWRZ and the most frequently active portion of the ERZ is typically <4âyr. These residence and storage times are short because the volume of magma within the plumbing system is relatively small (<0Â·5âkm3 for the summit reservoir, and probably much less for the SWRZ and UERZ to MERZ) compared to the typical rate of magma supply (up to â¼0Â·1â0Â·2âkm3/yr during the PuÊ»u Ê»ÅÊ»Å eruption; Dvorak & Dzurisin, 1993; Poland et al., 2012). These factors indicate that the âtop downâ crustal process of magma mixing at KÄ«lauea is insufficient to fully mask the âbottom upâ mantle source- and melting-related processes. Targeted studies of KÄ«lauea lavas, and their olivine-hosted melt inclusions (e.g. Sides et al., 2014), from eruptions that: (1) partially or completely bypass the summit reservoir and/or (2) extend beyond the short â¼2â3âyr (summit) or <4âyr (rift zone) time scales of magma mixing will provide the best opportunity to directly witness the production and mixing of incipient melts within the heterogeneous Hawaiian mantle plume.

One or more deeper summit magma reservoirs, possibly at the base of the volcanic edifice and/or the Pacific oceanic crust, have been suggested to exist (generally) for shield-stage Hawaiian volcanoes, and in particular, KÄ«lauea (e.g. Wright, 1971; Clague, 1987; Lynn et al., 2017). The short residence time of magma for KÄ«lauea summit lavas indicates that mantle-derived magma batches are not stored for long periods of time in a large crustal reservoir. Any deeper magma body must have a volume that is similar to or smaller than the summit reservoir (<0Â·5âkm3) in order to efficiently transmit the rapid, mantle-derived compositional fluctuations of KÄ«lauea lavas from the source to the surface. This inference is consistent with the deficits of short-lived 210Pb (t1/2â¼22âyr) relative to 226Ra in young KÄ«lauea lavas, which imply (via modeling of CO2 degassing) that magma ascends rapidly (on a time scale of only â¼8âyears) from mantle depths of â¼30âkm (Girard et al., 2017). The sum of these factorsâa high rate of melt supply and transport from the mantle, a lack of long-term magma storage in a large, deep crustal reservoir, and short magma residence and storage times in the shallow plumbing systemâmay account for the observation that contamination by the Hawaiian volcanic edifice or the Pacific oceanic crust has not significantly affected the Pb, Sr, and Nd isotopic composition of KÄ«lauea lavas.

The behavior for KÄ«lauea outlined in this study contrasts with Piton de la Fournaise (RÃ©union Island), a basaltic volcano in the Indian Ocean that is frequently active, and like KÄ«lauea, has a summit caldera with a large pit crater, and rift zones (e.g. Di Muro et al., 2014; Michon et al., 2015). However, the overall rate of magma supply to Piton de la Fournaise is an order of magnitude lower than KÄ«lauea, and its rift zones are less well developed (e.g. Peltier et al., 2015). Summit eruptions at Piton de la Fournaise are thought to be supplied (e.g. Famin et al., 2009; Peltier et al., 2009; PrÃ´no et al., 2009; Di Muro et al., 2014) from a multi-tiered reservoir, composed of a deep magma body near the base of the oceanic crust (â¼7Â·5âkm deep), in addition to a shallow magma body near sea level (â¼2Â·5âkm deep) and a near-surface complex of partially solidified dikes and sills (<1âkm deep). Estimates for the volume of magma within the shallow body (based on lava chemistry) range from â¼0Â·1 to 0Â·4âkm3 (AlbarÃ¨de, 1993; Sigmarsson et al., 2005; VlastÃ©lic et al., 2009), which is remarkably similar to our estimate for KÄ«laueaâs summit reservoir during the late 20th century. The volume of magma within the deeper part of the plumbing system of Piton de la Fournaise is unknown.

Historical lavas from Piton de la Fournaise display short-term, correlated variations in Sr isotope and incompatible element (e.g. Nd/Sm or Th/Yb) ratios that are thought to result mostly from the sampling of small-scale compositional heterogeneities in the mantle source (i.e. the RÃ©union plume) without large variations in the degree of partial melting (e.g. Pietruszka et al., 2009). The Pb isotope ratios of these lavas vary systematically (but do not correlate simply with either their Sr isotope or incompatible element ratios) and occasionally show large shifts towards highly unradiogenic Pb isotopic signatures during periods of high magma flux and picrite eruption (e.g. VlastÃ©lic et al., 2007, 2009). These fluctuations in the Pb isotope ratios of lavas from Piton de la Fournaise are thought to result partly from the assimilation of Pb-rich sulfides in the lithosphere that are genetically unrelated to RÃ©union magmatism (e.g. VlastÃ©lic & Pietruszka, 2016). In addition, the incompatible element ratios and 230Thâ238U disequilibria of some historical lavas from Piton de la Fournaise are anomalous due to the contamination of mantle-derived magmas with small amounts (â¼3â6%) of low-degree (<1%) partial melts of young, hydrothermally altered gabbro and wehrlite cumulates within the volcanic edifice. Unlike KÄ«lauea, crustal contamination is an important process at Piton de la Fournaise (e.g. VlastÃ©lic et al., 2005; SalaÃ¼n et al., 2010) that complicates our ability to identify and track mantle-derived magma batches through the volcanoâs plumbing system. The prevalence of crustal contamination at Piton de la Fournaise might be partly related to its relatively low magma supply rate and/or the slow motion of the Indian oceanic lithosphere over the RÃ©union plume (e.g. VlastÃ©lic & Pietruszka, 2016). Future studies are required to determine the detailed factors that control the interplay of mantle (source- and melting-related) vs crustal (mixing- and contamination-related) magmatic processes at these and other basaltic volcanoes.
